00:02:33.340 --> 00:02:35.930
NARRATOR: After checking in, the
students get introduced to

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:37.670
a technique called
nuclear magnetic

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:40.860
resonance, or NMR for short.

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:44.810
NMR helps chemists piece
together a molecule structure.

00:02:44.810 --> 00:02:48.390
The students put their mystery
molecule into a thin tube and

00:02:48.390 --> 00:02:51.810
lower it into a very powerful
magnetic field.

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:55.130
This forces certain atoms in the
sample to align themselves

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:57.930
either with or against
the field.

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:00.440
Aligning with the field
takes less energy.

00:03:00.440 --> 00:03:02.810
So there are a few more
atoms aligned with

00:03:02.810 --> 00:03:04.870
than against the field.

00:03:04.870 --> 00:03:07.580
A pulse of energy makes the
extra atoms aligned with the

00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:09.290
field flip.

00:03:09.290 --> 00:03:12.470
The computer measures how much
energy this takes and produces

00:03:12.470 --> 00:03:13.970
a spectrum.

00:03:13.970 --> 00:03:17.280
The amount of energy it takes
to flip an atom depends on

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.350
what other atoms
are next to it.

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:22.890
That means you can tell which of
the atoms are connected and

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:26.460
put together a picture of what
the whole molecule looks like.

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:27.890
That's the theory.

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:30.290
But the students are about to
learn that dealing with a real

00:03:30.290 --> 00:03:33.160
live machine is not so simple.

00:03:33.160 --> 00:03:34.447
ANNE RACHUPKA: Awful lot
we're going to go over.

00:03:34.447 --> 00:03:36.395
These are live magnets.

00:03:36.395 --> 00:03:38.343
They are in field
at all times.

00:03:38.343 --> 00:03:43.213
You cannot go anywhere near it
with iPod, iPhone, any USB

00:03:43.213 --> 00:03:47.109
storage devices, no push pins,
no staples, no bobby pins.

00:03:47.109 --> 00:03:49.070
